>.","2  English: variant of   End   with a prosthetic  <i>H-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Henkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Doron, Hyman.","English (Middlesex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Henekin</i>, <i>Hendekin</i>, a pet form of   Henry  . Compare   Hankin   1 and   Henn  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Khenke</i> (a pet form of Yiddish <i>Khane</i>, from Hebrew <i>Ḥanna</i>; see   Hanna   6) + the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>."]},{"name":"End","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(atten) ende</i>, denoting someone who lived at the end of a village or other settlement."]},{"name":"Henderson","meanings":["English and Scottish: usually from Middle English and Older Scots <i>Hener(i)son</i> ‘Henry's son’, occasionally from Middle English <i>Hendeson</i> ‘son of <i>Hen</i>’, a pet form of   Henry  , both with an intrusive <i>-d-</i>. Compare   Hendrie  . In Scotland <i>Henderson</i> was sometimes substituted for   McKendrick  ."]},{"name":"Henn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Otto, Siegfried, Ulrike, Aloysius, Bernhard, Heinz, Hermann, Herta, Jurgen, Kurt, Manfred.","English: from the personal name <i>Henn</i>, which, like <i>Hann</i>, was a pet form of <i>Henry</i>. Compare   Henkin  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>hen(ne)</i> ‘hen’ (Old English <i>henn</i>, related to <i>hana</i> ‘cock’), for someone thought to resemble a hen in some way, or perhaps from Middle English <i>hen</i> ‘poor man, rascal’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jo